  <article class="article-body">

    <p>devopsellence and Kubernetes solve different problems at different scales, but they share architectural DNA. Both use node-level agents that reconcile desired state into running containers. Both separate the control plane from the data plane. Both use declarative configuration.</p>

    <p>The differences are in what each system optimizes for. Kubernetes optimizes for multi-tenant orchestration across large clusters. devopsellence optimizes for deploying applications to your own servers with minimal operational overhead. This article maps each Kubernetes component to its devopsellence counterpart and explains what changes when you strip orchestration to its minimum useful form.</p>

    <h2>kube-proxy vs. Envoy per node</h2>

    <p>In Kubernetes, kube-proxy runs on every node and programs iptables or IPVS rules to route Service traffic to the correct pods. When pods are created, destroyed, or rescheduled, kube-proxy updates these rules. Pod IPs are ephemeral &mdash; they're assigned from the cluster CIDR when a pod starts and released when it stops. In a busy cluster, IP churn is constant: every scaling event, every rolling update, every node drain triggers rule updates across every node.</p>

    <p>devopsellence runs Envoy on every node instead. The agent embeds an xDS control plane server that Envoy connects to over a local Unix domain socket. When the agent needs to change routing (during a deploy), it pushes a new Endpoint Discovery Service (EDS) snapshot to Envoy. Envoy picks it up within milliseconds and starts routing traffic to the new container.</p>

    <p>The key difference is <strong>IP stability through reduced churn</strong>. In devopsellence, a container is replaced only when the desired state changes &mdash; a new deploy, a configuration change, or drift recovery. There's no rescheduling, no bin-packing, no eviction. A production container might run for days or weeks without replacement. When it is replaced, the agent inspects the new container's IP from the Docker bridge network and pushes it to Envoy in a single atomic EDS update. There's no cascading rule update across multiple nodes because each node's Envoy only knows about its own containers.</p>

    <p>Kubernetes kube-proxy is a distributed routing table that must stay consistent across the cluster. devopsellence's per-node Envoy is a local reverse proxy that only knows about one upstream. The failure domain is a single node, not the cluster.</p>

    <h2>etcd vs. Cloud Storage</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes stores all cluster state in etcd &mdash; a distributed key-value store that uses Raft consensus to guarantee strong consistency. Every pod spec, every service endpoint, every config map lives in etcd. The API server is a frontend for etcd, and controllers use etcd's watch mechanism to react to state changes in real time.</p>

    <p>This is powerful but operationally demanding. etcd requires at least 3 nodes for high availability. It needs fast disks (etcd is latency-sensitive). It needs backup, monitoring, compaction, and defragmentation. etcd failures can bring down the entire cluster's control plane.</p>

    <p>devopsellence stores desired state in Google Cloud Storage. Each node's desired state is a signed JSON envelope written to an immutable, sequence-indexed GCS object (e.g., <code>desired-states/000000000042.json</code>). A mutable pointer object redirects agents to the latest immutable envelope. Agents poll GCS every 2 seconds.</p>

    <p>GCS is not a consensus system. There's no watch mechanism, no real-time notification. Agents poll. But GCS provides properties that matter for this use case:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>No operational burden.</strong> GCS is a managed service. No nodes to provision, no backups to configure, no compaction to schedule.</li>
      <li><strong>Global availability.</strong> GCS is designed for 99.99% availability with automatic replication. A single regional etcd cluster can't match this.</li>
      <li><strong>Immutable history.</strong> Sequence-indexed objects are never overwritten. Every desired state ever published is preserved. etcd compacts old revisions to save space.</li>
      <li><strong>Decoupled reads.</strong> Agents read from GCS independently of the control plane. If the control plane (the writer) goes down, agents continue reading the last-published state. In Kubernetes, if the API server goes down, kubelets can't fetch updated pod specs (though existing pods keep running).</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The trade-off is latency and consistency. etcd's watch gives sub-second notification of changes. GCS polling adds up to 2 seconds of latency. etcd guarantees linearizable reads. GCS is eventually consistent (though in practice, consistency is near-instant for single-object reads). For a deployment tool where convergence within 2-4 seconds is acceptable, these trade-offs are worth the operational simplicity.</p>

    <p>devopsellence uses monotonically increasing sequence numbers to prevent rollback &mdash; analogous to etcd's revision numbers. Agents reject any envelope with a sequence number lower than the highest they've seen. This prevents a GCS consistency anomaly (reading a stale object) from causing a rollback to old state.</p>

    <h2>kubelet vs. devopsellence agent</h2>

    <p>Both are reconciliation loops running on each node. The kubelet watches the API server for pod specs assigned to its node, then reconciles containers via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI). The devopsellence agent polls GCS for a desired-state envelope, then reconciles containers via the Docker API.</p>

    <p>The kubelet's scope is broad:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Container lifecycle (create, start, stop, remove) via CRI (containerd)</li>
      <li>Volume mounting (PersistentVolumes, ConfigMaps, Secrets as files)</li>
      <li>Networking setup via CNI (pod network namespace, IP assignment)</li>
      <li>Resource enforcement (cgroups for CPU/memory limits)</li>
      <li>Liveness, readiness, and startup probes</li>
      <li>Log management and metrics collection</li>
      <li>Device plugin management (GPUs, etc.)</li>
      <li>Node status reporting (capacity, conditions, addresses)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The devopsellence agent's scope is narrow:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Container lifecycle (create, start, stop, remove) via Docker API</li>
      <li>Health checks for web services</li>
      <li>Envoy xDS management for traffic routing</li>
      <li>Secret resolution from GCP Secret Manager</li>
      <li>Status reporting to the control plane</li>
    </ul>

    <p>No volume management (Docker handles it). No networking setup (Docker bridge handles it). No resource enforcement (one app per node, so it gets everything). No device plugins. No log aggregation. The agent manages at most three containers: one web service, one optional worker, and Envoy. The kubelet might manage dozens of pods with hundreds of containers on a single node.</p>

    <p>This narrowness is the point. Every feature the kubelet has exists because multi-tenant orchestration requires it. When you remove multi-tenancy, you remove the need for most of those features.</p>

    <h2>Per-environment identity vs. Kubernetes ServiceAccounts</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes uses ServiceAccounts for workload identity. Each namespace has a default ServiceAccount. Pods can be bound to a specific ServiceAccount, which gives them an OIDC token mounted as a projected volume. RBAC policies control what API operations each ServiceAccount can perform. For cloud access, GKE Workload Identity (or similar) exchanges the ServiceAccount token for a cloud IAM credential.</p>

    <p>devopsellence assigns each environment a dedicated GCP service account. When the agent on a node needs to access GCP resources (pull images from Artifact Registry, fetch secrets from Secret Manager, read desired state from GCS), it uses Workload Identity Federation to exchange a control-plane-issued JWT for a short-lived GCP access token scoped to that environment's service account.</p>

    <p>The practical difference is <strong>isolation by default</strong>. In Kubernetes, pods in the same namespace share a ServiceAccount unless you explicitly create separate ones and bind them. RBAC policies must be written and maintained. Misconfiguration can grant one workload access to another's secrets.</p>

    <p>In devopsellence, each environment gets its own GCP service account automatically during provisioning. IAM bindings grant access only to that environment's secrets, that environment's GCS path, and that organization's image registry. This isn't application-level access control that can be bypassed by a bug &mdash; it's GCP IAM enforcement. An agent running your staging environment literally cannot access your production secrets, even if the agent code has a vulnerability, because the GCP access token doesn't have the IAM binding.</p>

    <h2>Secrets: etcd vs. Secret Manager</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes stores Secrets in etcd. They're base64-encoded (not encrypted) by default. With encryption at rest enabled, they're encrypted with a key that the API server manages. Any pod in the namespace can mount any Secret in that namespace unless you configure RBAC and admission policies to prevent it.</p>

    <p>devopsellence stores secret values in GCP Secret Manager. The control plane database stores only metadata: the secret name, a SHA256 digest for change detection, and the GCP resource path. The actual value is in Secret Manager, accessible only to the environment's GCP service account via IAM.</p>

    <p>The differences compound:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Database compromise.</strong> In Kubernetes, an etcd breach exposes all secrets (unless encryption at rest is configured with an external KMS). In devopsellence, a database breach exposes secret names and digests, not values.</li>
      <li><strong>Access audit.</strong> Kubernetes can log API server access, but requires explicit audit policy configuration. Secret Manager logs every access automatically in Cloud Audit Logs.</li>
      <li><strong>Rotation.</strong> Kubernetes Secrets require updating the Secret object and restarting pods to pick up new values. Secret Manager supports versioning natively &mdash; the agent always fetches <code>/versions/latest</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Cross-environment isolation.</strong> In Kubernetes, namespace-level isolation requires correct RBAC configuration. In devopsellence, isolation is enforced by GCP IAM &mdash; the agent's token simply can't reach another environment's secrets.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Ingress: controllers vs. per-node TLS termination</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes ingress typically involves an Ingress Controller (Nginx Ingress, Traefik, Envoy Gateway) running as a pod in the cluster, with a cloud load balancer in front. The Ingress Controller holds TLS private keys for every domain it terminates. cert-manager automates Let's Encrypt certificate issuance and renewal. The private keys are stored as Kubernetes Secrets in etcd.</p>

    <p>devopsellence's direct DNS ingress mode works differently. The agent generates an RSA key pair on the server. Only the Certificate Signing Request (containing the public key) is sent to the control plane. The control plane coordinates Let's Encrypt issuance via DNS-01 challenge and returns the signed certificate. The private key never leaves the server. Envoy terminates TLS locally using the key and certificate loaded via xDS.</p>

    <p><strong>Private key locality</strong> is the key difference. In the Kubernetes model, a compromise of the Ingress Controller (or etcd, or any pod that can read the Secret) exposes every TLS private key. In devopsellence, each server holds only its own key. A server compromise exposes one key, not all of them. The control plane never sees the private key at all &mdash; it only handles CSRs and certificates.</p>

    <h2>Rolling updates: ReplicaSets vs. atomic cutover</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes Deployments use ReplicaSets to manage rolling updates. You configure <code>maxSurge</code> (how many extra pods can exist during update) and <code>maxUnavailable</code> (how many pods can be down). The Deployment controller gradually scales up the new ReplicaSet while scaling down the old one. Readiness probes gate traffic &mdash; a pod only receives traffic after its readiness probe passes.</p>

    <p>devopsellence runs a single replica per service per node. There are no ReplicaSets, no surge, no gradual rollout across replicas. Instead, the agent performs an <strong>atomic cutover</strong> on each node independently:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>Start new container alongside the old one (both running simultaneously).</li>
      <li>Wait for the new container's health check to pass.</li>
      <li>Push an EDS update to Envoy, atomically routing all new requests to the new container.</li>
      <li>Wait a drain delay for in-flight requests to the old container to complete.</li>
      <li>Stop and remove the old container.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>If the new container fails its health check, the old container keeps serving. The failed container is removed. The deploy is reported as failed. At no point does the node serve traffic from an unhealthy container.</p>

    <p>The Kubernetes model is more flexible &mdash; it handles multiple replicas, canary deploys, and gradual rollouts. devopsellence's model is simpler because there's only one replica to manage. The zero-downtime guarantee comes from the same mechanism (health check gates traffic), just applied to a single container instead of a fleet of pods.</p>

    <h2>Scheduling: automated vs. explicit</h2>

    <p>The Kubernetes scheduler is a sophisticated component. It watches for unscheduled pods, scores each node based on available resources, affinity/anti-affinity rules, taints and tolerations, topology spread constraints, and priority classes. It makes placement decisions automatically &mdash; you describe what you want, and the scheduler decides where it runs.</p>

    <p>devopsellence has no scheduler. You assign nodes to environments explicitly:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">Assignment vs. scheduling</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code># Kubernetes: declare intent, scheduler decides placement
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
# scheduler picks nodes based on resources, affinity, taints...

# devopsellence: explicit assignment
devopsellence node attach NODE_ID --env production
# you pick the node, system validates and provisions identity</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Nodes have labels (<code>web</code>, <code>worker</code>) that determine which services they run, and capabilities (<code>direct_dns_ingress.v1</code>, <code>release_task.v1</code>) that determine which features they support. The control plane validates that the assignment is valid &mdash; a direct DNS environment can't be assigned to a node that doesn't support TLS termination &mdash; but the human makes the placement decision.</p>

    <p>This works because the problem is simple. When you have 1-10 servers and 1-5 environments, there's no bin-packing optimization to perform. You know which server should run production. You know which server is for staging. Automated scheduling adds complexity without solving a problem you have.</p>

    <h2>Control plane availability</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes requires at least 3 control plane nodes for high availability: 3 etcd members for Raft consensus, load-balanced API servers, redundant controller managers and schedulers. Losing quorum (2 of 3 etcd nodes) makes the cluster read-only. Losing the API server entirely prevents new scheduling, scaling, and configuration changes.</p>

    <p>devopsellence runs a single control plane (a Rails application backed by PostgreSQL). There's no consensus protocol, no quorum requirement. If the control plane goes down:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Running applications continue serving traffic. Agents reconcile from cached desired state in GCS (or on-disk cache if GCS is also unavailable).</li>
      <li>New deploys can't be published (the CLI can't reach the control plane).</li>
      <li>Token refresh will eventually expire (access tokens have a 1-hour TTL).</li>
      <li>When the control plane comes back, agents resume normal operation without manual intervention.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This is a weaker availability guarantee than Kubernetes HA. But it's a simpler operational model. You run one instance of the control plane. If it goes down, your apps keep running. You fix it and everything resumes. There's no split-brain scenario, no quorum loss, no etcd recovery procedure.</p>

    <p>The reason this works is the <strong>decoupled data plane</strong>. Agents don't need the control plane for runtime operations &mdash; they need GCS, Secret Manager, and Artifact Registry, all of which are independently highly available managed services. The control plane is only needed for management operations: publishing deploys, managing environments, rotating tokens.</p>

    <h2>The structural mapping</h2>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">Component mapping</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>Kubernetes                    devopsellence
─────────────────────────     ──────────────────────────────
etcd                       →  GCS (signed, immutable objects)
kube-apiserver             →  Control plane API (Rails)
kube-scheduler             →  Explicit assignment + labels
kubelet                    →  Agent (Go binary)
kube-proxy (iptables)      →  Envoy (xDS, per node)
CNI (pod networking)       →  Docker bridge network
ServiceAccount + RBAC      →  Per-env GCP SA + IAM
Secrets (in etcd)          →  GCP Secret Manager
Ingress Controller         →  Per-node Envoy + TLS termination
Deployment + ReplicaSet    →  Atomic single-replica cutover
ConfigMap                  →  Env vars in desired state
PersistentVolume           →  Docker volumes (single-node only)
Namespace                  →  Environment
Node                       →  Node (1:1, same concept)
Pod                        →  Container (no pod abstraction)</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Different problems, shared principles</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes and devopsellence share the same fundamental principles: declarative desired state, node-level reconciliation, health-gated traffic routing, and control plane / data plane separation. The difference is in what they optimize for.</p>

    <p>Kubernetes optimizes for <strong>generality and scale</strong>. It can run any workload, at any scale, on any infrastructure, with arbitrary scheduling constraints. This generality comes at a cost: operational complexity, configuration surface area, and a learning curve that takes months to navigate.</p>

    <p>devopsellence optimizes for <strong>simplicity and directness</strong>. It runs your web application on your servers with zero-downtime deploys, managed HTTPS, and production-grade security. It does this with a single binary on each server, no cluster infrastructure, and a deploy command that fits on one line.</p>

    <p>If your problem is "deploy my web app to my servers," devopsellence gives you a shorter path to production. If your problem is "orchestrate a fleet of microservices across a shared cluster," Kubernetes is the right tool. The architectural principles are the same. The scope is different.</p>

